# Domain Object Null Safety

Before accessing any method on a domain object (value objects, entities, compounds, aggregates, etc.), **MUST verify** that the object exists (is not `null` or `undefined`).

## General Principle: Verify Before Access

**ALWAYS verify domain object existence** before calling methods like `.toString()`, `.getValue()`, `.equals()`, `.hasValue()`, `.getId()`, `.getName()`, etc.

This rule applies to:
- **Value Objects**: `Id`, `Name`, `Slug`, `Title`, `Address`, etc.
- **Entities**: `User`, `Category`, `Event`, `City`, `Tag`, etc.
- **Compounds**: Objects that combine multiple domain entities (e.g., `PostWithProfile`)
- **Aggregates**: Root entities and their child entities
- **Domain Services**: Service instances accessed through dependency injection

This rule applies **regardless** of whether the object can technically be null based on its type definition. Verification is required to ensure runtime safety.

## Optional Domain Objects

When a domain object (value object, entity, compound, etc.) can be `undefined` or `null` (marked as optional in type signatures), verification is **mandatory**.

### ✅ CORRECT - Verifying Optional Value Object Before Access

```typescript
async findByWithPagination(
  categoryId: CategoryId | undefined,
  search: SearchQuery,
): Promise<{ events: Event[]; count: number }> {
  const where: Prisma.EventWhereInput = {
    // ... other conditions
  }

  // ✅ Verify existence before accessing methods
  if (categoryId && categoryId.hasCategory()) {
    where.categories = { some: { id: categoryId.toString() } }
  }

  if (search && search.hasQuery()) {
    where.OR = [
      { description: { contains: search.toString(), mode: 'insensitive' } },
    ]
  }

  // ...
}
```

### ✅ CORRECT - Verifying Optional Entity Before Access

```typescript
async processEvent(event: Event | null): Promise<void> {
  // ✅ Verify entity exists before accessing methods
  if (!event) return

  const title = event.getTitle().toString()
  const description = event.getDescription()?.toString() ?? ''
  
  // ✅ Verify nested value objects from entity
  const address = event.getAddress()
  if (address && address.hasValue()) {
    await this.processAddress(address.toString())
  }
}

async updateCategory(
  categoryId: string,
  category: Category | null,
): Promise<void> {
  // ✅ Verify entity exists before methods
  if (!category) {
    throw new OneJsError('Category not found', 404)
  }

  // ✅ Safe to access methods after verification
  const name = category.getName().toString()
  const slug = category.getSlug().toString()
}
```

### ✅ CORRECT - Verifying Compound Objects

```typescript
async processPostWithProfile(
  post: PostWithProfile | undefined,
): Promise<void> {
  // ✅ Verify compound object exists
  if (!post) return

  // ✅ Verify nested entity before accessing
  const profile = post.getProfile()
  if (profile) {
    const username = profile.getUsername().toString()
    // Process profile
  }

  const postId = post.getId().toString()
  // Process post
}
```

### ✅ CORRECT - Using Optional Chaining

```typescript
async processEvent(event: Event | null): Promise<void> {
  // ✅ Verify existence before method access
  if (!event) return

  const title = event.getTitle().toString()
  const description = event.getDescription()?.toString() ?? ''
  
  // ✅ Optional chaining for nested value objects
  const address = event.getAddress()
  if (address && address.hasValue()) {
    await this.processAddress(address.toString())
  }
}
```

### ✅ CORRECT - Verifying in Conditional Logic

```typescript
function buildQuery(params: {
  categoryId?: CategoryId
  tagIds?: TagId[]
  search?: SearchQuery
}): Prisma.EventWhereInput {
  const where: Prisma.EventWhereInput = {}

  // ✅ Verify before accessing methods
  if (params.categoryId && params.categoryId.hasCategory()) {
    where.categories = { some: { id: params.categoryId.toString() } }
  }

  // ✅ Verify array of value objects
  if (params.tagIds && params.tagIds.length > 0) {
    where.tags = {
      some: { id: { in: params.tagIds.map((tag) => tag.getValue()) } },
    }
  }

  // ✅ Verify before calling methods
  if (params.search && params.search.hasQuery()) {
    where.OR = [{ title: { contains: params.search.toString() } }]
  }

  return where
}
```

### ❌ INCORRECT - Accessing Methods Without Verification

```typescript
async findByWithPagination(
  categoryId: CategoryId | undefined,
): Promise<{ events: Event[] }> {
  const where: Prisma.EventWhereInput = {
    // ❌ WRONG - categoryId might be undefined
    categories: { some: { id: categoryId.toString() } },
  }
  // This will throw if categoryId is undefined
}

async processOptional(vo: ValueObject | null): Promise<void> {
  // ❌ WRONG - vo might be null
  const value = vo.toString()
  // This will throw if vo is null
}
```

### ❌ INCORRECT - Missing Verification in Conditionals

```typescript
function buildQuery(categoryId?: CategoryId): Prisma.EventWhereInput {
  const where: Prisma.EventWhereInput = {}

  // ❌ WRONG - Missing verification before hasCategory()
  if (categoryId.hasCategory()) {
    // This will throw if categoryId is undefined
    where.categories = { some: { id: categoryId.toString() } }
  }

  return where
}
```

## Verification Methods

Many value objects provide verification methods. **Use them when available** before accessing other methods:

- `hasValue()` - Check if value object has a meaningful value
- `hasCategory()` - Check if category value object has a category
- `isEmpty()` - Check if value object is empty

### ✅ CORRECT - Using Verification Methods

```typescript
async processAddress(address: Address | undefined): Promise<void> {
  // ✅ Check existence first
  if (!address) return

  // ✅ Use hasValue() before other methods
  if (address.hasValue()) {
    await this.saveAddress(address.toString())
  }

  // ✅ Check isEmpty() before accessing value
  if (!address.isEmpty()) {
    const length = address.getValue().length
  }
}
```

### ✅ CORRECT - Compound Verification

```typescript
async filterEvents(
  categoryId: CategoryId | undefined,
  search: SearchQuery,
): Promise<Event[]> {
  const where: Prisma.EventWhereInput = {}

  // ✅ Verify existence AND use verification method
  if (categoryId && categoryId.hasCategory()) {
    where.categories = { some: { id: categoryId.toString() } }
  }

  // ✅ Verify before calling methods
  if (search && search.hasQuery()) {
    where.OR = [{ title: { contains: search.toString() } }]
  }

  return this.repository.findMany(where)
}
```

## Accessing Objects Through Other Objects

When accessing domain objects through other domain objects (value objects from entities, entities from compounds, etc.), verify the accessed object exists:

### ✅ CORRECT - Verifying Value Objects from Entities

```typescript
async processEvent(event: Event | null): Promise<void> {
  // ✅ Verify entity first
  if (!event) return

  // ✅ Value objects from entities should be verified if they can be optional
  const address = event.getAddress()
  
  if (address && address.hasValue()) {
    await this.geocodeAddress(address.toString())
  }

  const description = event.getDescription()
  if (description) {
    const text = description.toString()
    // Process description
  }
}
```

### ✅ CORRECT - Optional Chaining for Nested Access

```typescript
function formatEventDisplay(event: Event | null): string {
  // ✅ Verify entity first
  if (!event) return ''

  // ✅ Verify nested value objects
  const venue = event.getVenue()
  const venueName = venue?.getName()
  
  return venueName && venueName.hasValue()
    ? `${event.getTitle().toString()} at ${venueName.toString()}`
    : event.getTitle().toString()
}
```

### ✅ CORRECT - Verifying Entities from Compound Objects

```typescript
async processPostWithProfile(post: PostWithProfile): Promise<void> {
  // ✅ Verify compound object exists (should be done at caller, but double-check if needed)
  if (!post) return

  // ✅ Verify nested entity before accessing methods
  const profile = post.getProfile()
  if (profile) {
    // ✅ Safe to access profile methods
    const username = profile.getUsername().toString()
    const instagramId = profile.getInstagramId().toString()
  }
}
```

## Arrays of Domain Objects

When working with arrays of domain objects (value objects, entities, etc.), verify the array exists and optionally verify elements:

### ✅ CORRECT - Verifying Array of Value Objects

```typescript
async processTags(tagIds: TagId[] | undefined): Promise<void> {
  // ✅ Verify array exists and has elements
  if (!tagIds || tagIds.length === 0) return

  // ✅ Each element is verified by iteration
  const ids = tagIds.map((tagId) => tagId.toString())

  await this.repository.findByTags(ids)
}
```

### ✅ CORRECT - Verifying Array of Entities

```typescript
function extractTagNames(tags: Tag[] | null): string[] {
  // ✅ Verify array exists and has elements
  if (!tags || tags.length === 0) return []

  // ✅ Safe to access methods after verification
  return tags.map((tag) => tag.getName().toString())
}

async processEvents(events: Event[] | undefined): Promise<void> {
  // ✅ Verify array exists
  if (!events || events.length === 0) return

  // ✅ Safe to access entity methods
  for (const event of events) {
    const title = event.getTitle().toString()
    const cityId = event.getCityId().toString()
    // Process event
  }
}
```

### ❌ INCORRECT - Accessing Methods on Undefined Array

```typescript
async processTags(tagIds: TagId[] | undefined): Promise<void> {
  // ❌ WRONG - tagIds might be undefined
  const ids = tagIds.map((tagId) => tagId.toString())
  // This will throw if tagIds is undefined
}
```

## Use Cases

In use cases, verify value objects from input parameters:

### ✅ CORRECT - Verification in Use Cases

```typescript
@Injectable()
export class FilterEventsUseCase {
  async execute(input: {
    cityId: CityId
    categoryId?: CategoryId
    search?: SearchQuery
    tags?: TagId[]
  }): Promise<Event[]> {
    const where: Prisma.EventWhereInput = {
      cityId: input.cityId.getValue(), // Required, no check needed
    }

    // ✅ Verify optional value objects
    if (input.categoryId && input.categoryId.hasCategory()) {
      where.categories = { some: { id: input.categoryId.toString() } }
    }

    // ✅ Verify optional search
    if (input.search && input.search.hasQuery()) {
      where.OR = [{ title: { contains: input.search.toString() } }]
    }

    // ✅ Verify optional array
    if (input.tags && input.tags.length > 0) {
      where.tags = {
        some: { id: { in: input.tags.map((tag) => tag.getValue()) } },
      }
    }

    return this.repository.findMany(where)
  }
}
```

### ❌ INCORRECT - Missing Verification in Use Cases

```typescript
@Injectable()
export class FilterEventsUseCase {
  async execute(input: {
    categoryId?: CategoryId
    search?: SearchQuery
  }): Promise<Event[]> {
    const where: Prisma.EventWhereInput = {}

    // ❌ WRONG - Missing verification
    where.categories = { some: { id: input.categoryId.toString() } }

    // ❌ WRONG - Missing verification
    where.OR = [{ title: { contains: input.search.toString() } }]

    return this.repository.findMany(where)
  }
}
```

## Repository Methods

In repository methods, verify value objects before using them in queries:

### ✅ CORRECT - Verification in Repositories

```typescript
async findByComplex(
  categoryId?: CategoryId,
  search?: SearchQuery,
): Promise<Event[]> {
  const where: Prisma.EventWhereInput = {}

  // ✅ Verify before using in query
  if (categoryId && categoryId.hasCategory()) {
    where.categories = { some: { id: categoryId.toString() } }
  }

  if (search && search.hasQuery()) {
    where.OR = [{ description: { contains: search.toString() } }]
  }

  const dtos = await this.prisma.event.findMany({ where })
  return dtos.map((dto) => Event.fromDto(dto))
}
```

## Value Object Methods That Return Optional

Some value object methods return `null` or `undefined`. Verify the result before using:

### ✅ CORRECT - Verifying Optional Method Results

```typescript
async processOptionalPrice(price: Price | null): Promise<void> {
  if (!price) return

  // ✅ Some methods return optional values - verify result
  const optionalPrice = Price.createOptional(priceString)
  if (optionalPrice) {
    const amount = optionalPrice.getAmount()
    // Process amount
  }
}
```

## Rules Summary

### ✅ DO

- **ALWAYS verify** domain object existence before accessing methods (value objects, entities, compounds, aggregates)
- Verify entities before accessing their getters: `if (entity) { entity.getId() }`
- Verify value objects before method calls: `if (vo && vo.hasValue()) { vo.toString() }`
- Verify compounds before accessing nested entities: `if (compound) { compound.getEntity() }`
- Use explicit null/undefined checks: `if (obj && obj.hasValue())`
- Use optional chaining when appropriate: `obj?.toString() ?? ''`
- Verify arrays exist before iterating: `if (array && array.length > 0)`
- Use verification methods when available: `hasValue()`, `hasCategory()`, `isEmpty()`
- Verify optional domain objects in function parameters
- Combine existence checks with verification methods: `categoryId && categoryId.hasCategory()`
- Verify nested objects: entity → value object, compound → entity → value object

### ❌ DON'T DO

- Don't access methods without verifying existence: `categoryId.toString()` when `categoryId` might be `undefined`
- Don't access entity getters without verification: `entity.getId()` when `entity` might be `null`
- Don't access nested objects without verification: `compound.getEntity().getValue()` without checking both
- Don't assume domain objects are never null/undefined based on type alone
- Don't skip verification even if TypeScript types suggest safety
- Don't access methods on undefined arrays without checking first
- Don't call methods on domain objects without explicit verification in conditionals

